<h2>HVAC Systems in Louisiana</h2>
<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Louisiana's subtropical climate demands HVAC systems designed primarily for cooling efficiency, with heating requirements minimal compared to northern states. The state experiences approximately 2,400-2,800 cooling degree days annually versus only 1,500-2,200 heating degree days, indicating that air conditioning dominates energy consumption. Humidity levels frequently exceed 80% during summer months, making dehumidification capabilities essential for comfort and indoor air quality.</p>

<p>For Louisiana's climate, HVAC systems should feature SEER ratings of at least 16-18 for optimal efficiency, with higher-end systems reaching SEER 20-22 providing maximum savings during extended cooling seasons. Heat pump systems work exceptionally well in Louisiana due to mild winter temperatures, offering both efficient cooling and adequate heating for the few cold days each year. Central air conditioning systems should be properly sized to handle peak loads while maintaining humidity control, typically requiring 1 ton of cooling capacity per 400-500 square feet of living space in Louisiana's climate.</p>

